SECTION 3 — TOP ENTITY ANNUAL LICENSE FEE
================================================================================

3.1 A Top Entity that makes Qualifying Use owes the Annual License Fee for each
    calendar year in which it makes Qualifying Use while it qualifies as a Top
    Entity.

3.2 Within fifteen (15) days after its first Qualifying Use in each calendar
    year, a Top Entity must deliver written notice to the Licensor identifying:

    (a) its full legal name and jurisdiction of organization;

    (b) the date of first Qualifying Use in that calendar year;

    (c) a legal department contact or registered agent contact and a finance
        contact for payment communications; and

    (d) the Effective Market Capitalization tier it claims applies, together
        with the valuation basis for that claim.

3.3 The Annual License Fee for a given calendar year is due within thirty (30)
    days after the entity's first Qualifying Use of the Work in that calendar
    year. No invoice, reminder, or further demand from the Licensor is
    required.

3.4 If an entity changes tiers during a calendar year, the fee for that year is
    calculated on a prorated basis by applying the fee associated with each
    tier for the fraction of the year during which the entity was in that tier.
    Any additional amount caused by an upward tier change is due within thirty
    (30) days after the date that higher tier first applies. A claimed
    downward reclassification or loss of Top Entity status is effective only
    from the date established by contemporaneous records actually produced
    under Section 5. In the absence of such records, the highest reasonably
    supported tier applies through the remainder of the calendar year.

    A tier reclassification, whether upward or downward, takes effect only
    after the entity has remained in the new tier for at least seven (7)
    consecutive calendar days as measured by Effective Market Capitalization.
    If the entity's Effective Market Capitalization returns to the prior tier
    before completing the seven-day period, no reclassification occurs.
    Proration under this Section is calculated from the date the seven-day
    holding period completes, not from the date the valuation first changed.

3.5 All payments due under this License must be made free and clear of setoff,
    recoupment, counterclaim, or deduction, except for withholding required by
    law. If withholding is legally required, the paying entity must promptly
    provide documentation of that withholding and pay any additional amount
    lawfully necessary so that the Licensor receives the full amount that would
    have been received absent the withholding.

3.6 If a Top Entity fails to deliver the notice, certification, records, or
    payment required by this License when due, the Licensor may treat the
    earliest reasonably supported date of Qualifying Use and the highest
    reasonably supported tier as controlling unless and until the entity
    rebuts that determination with reliable contemporaneous records.

3.7 Unpaid fees accrue simple interest from the due date until paid at the
    lesser of:

    (a) ten percent (10%) per annum; or

    (b) the maximum lawful rate permitted by applicable law.

3.8 If a Top Entity fails to pay a due Annual License Fee or fails to deliver a
    required officer certification, the Licensor may provide written notice of
    non-payment or non-compliance. If the unpaid amount or missing
    certification remains outstanding thirty (30) days after that notice is
    delivered to the entity's legal department, registered agent, or last
    known legal counsel, the license granted by this License terminates as to
    that entity for future Qualifying Use unless and until the entity cures in
    full.

3.9 Payment is due in immediately available funds unless the Licensor elects in
    a separate signed writing to accept equity or another form of
    consideration. Acceptance of a partial payment, a late payment, or a
    request to discuss alternative consideration does not waive any remaining
    amount due and does not authorize continued Qualifying Use.

================================================================================
SECTION 4 — ANTI-EVASION, AGGREGATION, AND SUCCESSORS
================================================================================

4.1 "Common control" includes direct or indirect ownership of more than fifty
    percent (50%) of voting power, the power to appoint a majority of a board
    or similar governing body, or the power to direct management or policies
    by contract, financing, equity arrangement, or practical control. Entities
    under common control that are primarily structured, reorganized, or
    allocated in a manner designed to avoid Top Entity classification or to
    reduce fees otherwise due under this License may be aggregated and treated
    as a single entity for fee calculation purposes, to the extent permitted
    by applicable law.

4.2 A Top Entity may not avoid the Annual License Fee by causing a contractor,
    subsidiary, parent, affiliate, portfolio company, joint venture,
    foundation, research lab, cloud provider, reseller, API intermediary,
    nominee, or other intermediary to make Qualifying Use on its behalf, at
    its direction, with its funding, or primarily for its benefit. Such use is
    treated as use by the Top Entity.

4.3 A Top Entity is treated as making Qualifying Use if the Work is used to
    develop, train, test, operate, improve, deliver, or support products or
    services that the Top Entity sells, licenses, funds, directs, controls, or
    materially benefits from, whether or not another entity is the immediate
    user of the Work.

4.4 Any successor, acquirer, asset purchaser, or reorganized entity that
    continues Qualifying Use of the Work, or that acquires assets, models,
    systems, codebases, or business lines materially developed using the Work,
    assumes the payment and compliance obligations associated with that
    continuing Qualifying Use to the extent permitted by applicable law.

4.5 Any entity disputing its Top Entity status, fee tier, or attribution of
    Qualifying Use bears the burden of producing reasonably reliable financial,
    operational, and organizational records sufficient to support its claimed
    classification. Failure to segregate records or disclose control
    relationships is construed against the disputing entity.

================================================================================
SECTION 5 — RECORDS, CERTIFICATION, AND AUDIT
================================================================================

5.1 Each Top Entity must keep records reasonably sufficient to verify:

    (a) the dates of its first Qualifying Use in each calendar year;

    (b) the Effective Market Capitalization tier or tiers applicable during
        that year;

    (c) the calculation and payment of fees due under Section 3; and

    (d) the identity of any affiliates, contractors, vendors, or other
        intermediaries through which it contends Qualifying Use occurred.

5.2 The records described in Section 5.1 must be retained for at least four
    (4) years after the end of the applicable calendar year.

5.3 On or before the due date for the Annual License Fee, each Top Entity must
    deliver an officer certification summarizing the information described in
    Section 5.1 and confirming the entity's payment status under this License.

5.4 On reasonable written notice, no more than once per calendar year absent a
    good-faith basis to suspect underpayment, concealment, or evasion, the
    Licensor may require a Top Entity to provide supplemental records or an
    updated officer certification within twenty (20) business days.

5.5 If a Top Entity refuses to provide the certification or records required by
    this Section, or provides materially incomplete information, the Licensor
    may require an independent audit by a neutral accounting professional under
    reasonable confidentiality protections. If the audit reveals underpayment,
    underreporting, or a material reporting failure, the entity must promptly
    pay the deficiency, interest, and the reasonable cost of the audit.

5.6 Failure to produce requested records within the applicable deadline creates
    a rebuttable presumption that the Licensor's reasonably supported
    calculation of first Qualifying Use, tier, and amount due is correct.

