================================================================================
SECTION 8A — PRO BONO LITIGATION INCENTIVE
================================================================================

8A.1 PURPOSE. To make enforcement of this License feasible against well-funded
    adverse entities, the Licensor establishes the following opt-in program
    through which any qualified attorney may elect to represent the Licensor
    in disputes, negotiations, collections, audits, or enforcement actions
    arising out of or relating to this License.

8A.2 ATTORNEY OPT-IN. Any attorney licensed in a jurisdiction relevant to the
    matter may opt in by delivering written notice to the Licensor stating:

    (a) the specific matter or class of matters the attorney is accepting;

    (b) confirmation that no disqualifying conflict of interest exists;

    (c) the attorney's standard billing rate in effect at the time of opt-in
        (the "Standard Rate");

    (d) the disclosures and certifications required by Section 8B; and

    (e) whether the attorney elects Exclusive Allegiance status under Section
        8A.3(b) or Secondary Assistance status under Section 8A.3(c). An
        Exclusive Allegiance election requires a written pledge that the
        attorney will represent only the Licensor and his causes for the
        duration of representation under this License and for twelve (12)
        months thereafter, and will not accept any engagement adverse to the
        Licensor during that period.

8A.3 COMPENSATION STRUCTURE. Each attorney who validly opts in under Section
    8A.2 is entitled to the following compensation:

    (a) BASE RATE — REGARDLESS OF OUTCOME. The Licensor shall compensate each
        participating attorney at that attorney's Standard Rate for billable
        time spent on the matter, payable within thirty (30) days after
        invoice unless the parties agree otherwise in a separate writing.

    (b) EXCLUSIVE ALLEGIANCE POOL — WINS ONLY. Upon any Qualifying Recovery,
        the Licensor shall pay a success fee equal to twelve percent (12%) of
        the gross amount of that Qualifying Recovery to the Exclusive
        Allegiance Pool. The Exclusive Allegiance Pool fee is divided equally
        among the attorneys who (i) elected Exclusive Allegiance status under
        Section 8A.2(e), (ii) actively and materially participated in
        obtaining that specific Qualifying Recovery, and (iii) maintained
        their exclusivity pledge throughout the matter, as determined by the
        Licensor in good faith.

    (c) SECONDARY ASSISTANCE POOL — WINS ONLY. Upon any Qualifying Recovery,
        the Licensor shall pay a success fee equal to one percent (1%) of the
        gross amount of that Qualifying Recovery to the Secondary Assistance
        Pool. The Secondary Assistance Pool fee is divided equally among the
        attorneys who (i) elected Secondary Assistance status under Section
        8A.2(e), (ii) actively and materially participated in obtaining that
        specific Qualifying Recovery, and (iii) are not members of the
        Exclusive Allegiance Pool for that matter, as determined by the
        Licensor in good faith.

    (d) POOL ELECTION IS BINDING. An attorney's pool election under Section
        8A.2(e) is binding for the duration of the matter unless the Licensor
        consents in writing to a change. An Exclusive Allegiance attorney who
        breaches the exclusivity pledge forfeits eligibility for the
        Exclusive Allegiance Pool and may not retroactively claim Secondary
        Assistance Pool compensation for the same matter.

8A.4 QUALIFYING RECOVERY. "Qualifying Recovery" means any monetary payment
    actually received by the Licensor as a direct result of a judgment, order,
    settlement, consent decree, audit resolution, or other binding resolution
    in a matter in which the attorney actively and materially participated.
    Qualifying Recovery includes unpaid Annual License Fees, interest,
    settlements, judgments, and attorneys' fees shifted to the Licensor by
    court order or settlement. Qualifying Recovery excludes cost
    reimbursements paid directly to the Licensor and purely non-monetary
    relief with no monetary component.

8A.5 NO EXCLUSIVITY. Opt-in does not create an exclusive representation
    relationship. The Licensor may engage multiple attorneys in the same
    matter simultaneously.

8A.6 ATTORNEY INDEPENDENCE. Attorneys who opt in are retained as independent
    contractors, not employees, partners, or general agents of the Licensor.
    Each attorney remains bound by the professional-conduct rules applicable
    in the attorney's jurisdiction.

8A.7 LICENSOR RIGHTS. The Licensor retains the right to accept or decline any
    opt-in, terminate any attorney's representation subject to applicable
    professional-conduct rules, and settle, accept, or reject any offer at
    the Licensor's sole discretion so long as the settlement does not impose
    obligations directly on the attorney without that attorney's consent.

8A.8 STANDING OFFER. Publication of this License constitutes a standing offer
    to any attorney satisfying Sections 8A and 8B to enter this compensation
    arrangement. No separate signed engagement letter is required to activate
    the compensation structure described here, although the Licensor may use
    one in any particular matter.

================================================================================
SECTION 8B — DEFECTING COUNSEL, DOUBLE-AGENT, AND TRIPLE-AGENT SAFEGUARDS
================================================================================

8B.1 DEFECTING COUNSEL. Any attorney who, within the thirty-six (36) months
    preceding opt-in, was engaged by an entity adverse to the Licensor in a
    matter covered by this License, and who voluntarily terminates or
    withdraws from that engagement in order to represent the Licensor,
    qualifies as "Defecting Counsel" if the attorney satisfies this Section.

8B.2 DEFECTING COUNSEL SUCCESS FEE. In addition to the compensation under
    Section 8A, each Defecting Counsel who actively and materially
    participates in obtaining a Qualifying Recovery is entitled to an
    additional success fee equal to two percent (2%) of that Qualifying
    Recovery, divided equally among the Defecting Counsel who actively and
    materially participated in that specific recovery.

8B.3 GOOD-FAITH REQUIREMENT. Defecting Counsel status and the enhanced fee in
    Section 8B.2 apply only where the attorney switched representation in
    good faith, genuinely believes the Licensor's position has legal and
    factual merit, and is not acting as an agent, conduit, intermediary, or
    information channel for any adverse entity.

8B.4 DISCLOSURE AND VERIFICATION CHECKS. Each attorney opting in under Section
    8A must:

    (a) disclose any prior adverse-party relationship within the preceding
        thirty-six (36) months;

    (b) certify at opt-in that neither the attorney nor, to the attorney's
        knowledge after reasonable inquiry, the attorney's firm, employer,
        co-counsel, referral counsel, or litigation funder is acting as a
        double agent, triple agent, or other undisclosed conflicted
        intermediary for any entity adverse to the Licensor in the matter;

    (c) renew that certification every thirty (30) days during any active
        representation under this Section and within five (5) business days
        after any material change affecting the certification; and

    (d) on reasonable written request, provide sufficient non-privileged
        information to verify compliance with this Section, including current
        firm or employer identity, co-counsel relationships, referral
        arrangements, funding relationships, and any material adverse-party
        engagement relevant to the matter.

8B.5 NO DOUBLE OR TRIPLE AGENTS — LIABILITY FOR CAUSED LOSSES. The following
    provisions are absolute and non-waivable:

    (a) PROHIBITION. No participating attorney or Defecting Counsel may,
        directly or through intermediaries, maintain any undisclosed
        representation, advisory, employment, consulting, referral, funding,
        or information-sharing relationship with any entity adverse to the
        Licensor while representing the Licensor in the matter.

    (b) PERSONAL LIABILITY. Any participating attorney or Defecting Counsel
        who intentionally or through gross negligence acts as a double agent,
        triple agent, or similar conflicted intermediary is personally liable
        to the Licensor for the full amount of losses, damages, adverse
        judgments, settlement amounts, fee reductions, or other monetary harm
        causally attributable to that conduct.

    (c) DISGORGEMENT. Any compensation paid under Sections 8A or 8B to a
        participating attorney or Defecting Counsel who is later determined to
        have violated this Section is subject to full disgorgement, together
        with interest at the rate described in Section 3.7 from the date each
        payment was received.

    (d) PRESUMPTION AND BURDEN. A failure to make the disclosures,
        certifications, or verification response required by Section 8B.4
        creates a rebuttable presumption of breach. The accused attorney bears
        the burden of disproving material conflict, causation, and resulting
        harm.

8B.6 NO LIMITATION ON SECTION 8A. Nothing in this Section reduces the rights,
    compensation, or eligibility of attorneys who opt in under Section 8A and
    have no prior adverse-party relationship. Sections 8A and 8B operate in
    parallel.

